Scania (Skåne)

to 26 Feb 1658

Map of Skane Capital: Malmö

c.380 Semi-legendary Kingdom of Scania, ruled by Rex Scaniae.

c.930 One of the three united constituent parts (along with Jutland

and the Islands [Sealand]) of the Kingdom of Denmark.

1320 - 1332 Pawned by Denmark to Holstein.

1332 - 1360 In union with Sweden, the king of Sweden styled Rex Scaniae.

1370 - 1385 Occupied by the Hanseatic League.

26 Feb 1658 Ceded by Denmark-Norway to Sweden in the Treaty of Roskilde; autonomy

guaranteed with own assembly (Lantdagen). Skåne described

by Sweden as "domestic but foreign land", includes the

provinces of Scania (proper), Blekinge, Bornholm (returned to

Denmark 27 May 1660), Halland, and Trondheim (returned 27 May 1660).

The king of Sweden adds the style of "Duke of Skane" (Hertig av Skåne).

27 Jun 1676 - 4 Dec 1676 Occupied by Denmark.

1719 Re-organized into counties of Kristianstad and Malmöhus

(see Sweden counties).

1720 Autonomy abolished.

9 Feb 1801 - 27 Mar 1809 Office of governor-general restored.

Gotland

1288 - 1361 Visby a free city. 1358 - 1470 Visby a member of the Hanseatic League.27 Jul 1361 Gotland under Danish rule. 1392 - 5 Apr 1398 Pirate rule (called Vitalienbrüder ["Brothers of the Vitals"

or "Victuals", because they captured Hansa ships usually

transporting food during the war against Denmark). spring 1397 - 26 Jul 1397 Briefly occupied by Erik I, Duke of Mecklenburg (b. c.1365 - d.

1397), son of the deposed Swedish King Albrekt "af Mecklenburg"

(b. c.1338 - d. 1412).

5 Apr 1398 - Nov 1408 Teutonic Order rule. 13 Nov 1408 Sold to Denmark. 22 Dec 1448 Fully restored to Denmark (effective 20 Apr 1449).Jul 1525 - Aug 1526 Administered by the Imperial Free City of Lübeck. 23 Aug 1645 Annexed by Sweden (see Sweden counties). 1 May 1676 - Sep 1679 Occupied by Denmark. 24 Apr 1808 - 18 May 1808 Occupied by Russia.
